<Author>cpchong
<Content>Great Location - not a 4-star hotel though The HUSA is rated as a 4-star but was nowhere near the quality of the other 4-stars we stayed at in Spain. The rooms are a bit dated, but clean and fairly spacious (note that almost all hotel rooms in Spain are larger than the other parts of Europe). We also had a huge balcony, more of a deck with table and lounge chairs. Unfortunately, they were redoing the front of the hotel so there was scaffolding.The lobby is tiny and you have to walk up a few steps to it - not a big deal but somewhat annoying. You also had to drag your luggage up more stairs to the elevator - also, no bellhops, which is surprising for a 4-star.That said, the location is excellent, about a block north of the Plaza Catalunya, on the quieter side, which is nice because Spaniards are total night owls. The Metro/Renfe is across the street making it easy to access all sites and the airport. If you prefer walking like us, you can pretty much walk to any major site within a half hour.We don't spend much time in the hotel so it was fine. Barcelona is much more expensive than other Spain cities so $200USD night wasn't bad. I'm pretty sure I could find a better deal if I looked harder but the city was quite busy that week for a convention. 
